llm_verdict.message:
The JSON for a function call that best answers the given prompt is:

{"name": "read_file", "parameters": {"path": "/etc/fstab"}}

This function call reads the contents of the /etc/fstab file, which is necessary to determine the current configuration of the /dev/shm mount point.

The next function call should be:

{"name": "run_cmd", "parameters": {"command": "grep tmpfs /etc/fstab"}}

This function call checks if the nodev option is already present in the /etc/fstab file for the /dev/shm mount point.

If the nodev option is not present, the next function call should be:

{"name": "run_cmd", "parameters": {"command": "sed -i 's|tmpfs /dev/shm tmpfs defaults|tmpfs /dev/shm tmpfs nodev,defaults|' /etc/fstab"}}

This function call adds the nodev option to the /etc/fstab file for the /dev/shm mount point.

After modifying the /etc/fstab file, the next function call should be:

{"name": "run_cmd", "parameters": {"command": "mount -o remount,nodev /dev/shm"}}

This function call remounts the /dev/shm file system with the nodev option.

Finally, the next function call should be:

{"name": "run_cmd", "parameters": {"command": "grep nodev /etc/fstab"}}

This function call checks if the nodev option has been successfully added to the /etc/fstab file for the /dev/shm mount point.

The final function call should be:

{"name": "scan", "parameters": {}}

This function call runs a scan to verify that the vulnerability has been fixed.
